{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/a-short-guide-to-using-docker-for-your-data-science-environment-912617b3603e", "time": 1682994121.17042, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/a-short-guide-to-using-docker-for-your-data-science-environment-912617b3603e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "A Short Guide to Using Docker for Your Data Science Environment | by Nilesh | Towards Data Science", "h1": "A Short Guide to Using Docker for Your Data Science Environment", "description": "One of the most time consuming part of starting your work on a new system/starting a new job or just plain sharing your work is the variation of tools available (or lack thereof) due to differences\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.docker.com/resources/what-container", "anchor_text": "Containerization", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/docker.html", "anchor_text": "JetBrains", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://cloud.google.com/containers", "anchor_text": "Google Cloud", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://docs.docker.com/compose/bundles", "anchor_text": "Docker", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/builder", "anchor_text": "dockerfile", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://docs.docker.com/engine/reference/commandline/build", "anchor_text": "docker build", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://hub.docker.com/r/_/python", "anchor_text": "official repository for python from dockerhub", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://jupyter-docker-stacks.readthedocs.io", "anchor_text": "Jupyter Docker Stacks", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://github.com/nilesh-patil/datascience-environment", "anchor_text": "Github", "paragraph_index": 13}], "all_paragraphs": ["One of the most time consuming part of starting your work on a new system/starting a new job or just plain sharing your work is the variation of tools available (or lack thereof) due to differences in hardware/software/security policies and what not. Containerization has risen up in recent years as a ready to use solution to work around platform differences across a variety of applications from single user development environments (try out JetBrains tools with docker) to highly distributed production environments (e.g. Google Cloud, Docker ). In this article we\u2019ll go through Docker as our container service and steps needed to get started with building your custom development platform for data science.", "Personally, I believe that the ability to build upon other\u2019s systems is one of the biggest advantages while using docker. You can get started with simply cloning an already existing environment if it satisfies all your needs, or, you can build on top of it to make it even more useful for your specific use case using your dockerfile!", "Lets discuss a couple of scenarios :", "Approach A : Start with a base linux distro of your choice", "Say you decide that the best way to start is from scratch i.e. starting with your preferred linux distro and installing every software tailored to your need. In this way you have complete control over every single software being installed and you can install specific version for every tool as needed. This also potentially gives you the smallest image size as you can skip over any tools that you don\u2019t need. A couple of sample dockerfiles for this approach are shown below :", "That\u2019s all. Copy this to a file in an empty folder and build an image using docker build to get access to base python3 in ubuntu.", "Another way to build your image is to use the official repository for python from dockerhub. You can clone a image using docker pull command :", "Approach B : Use an already available image with all your tools installed", "This is the reason I have fallen in love with using docker for my day to day work. Folks at Jupyter Docker Stacks have created a number of well tested, fully functional and ready to use images with different tools already installed. A dependency tree taken from their documentation is shown below:", "Using these images or slight modifications to them should be sufficient for most use cases. To use one of these images, just use the \u201c docker run\u201d command and the image will be downloaded if its not already present.", "The -p argument mirrors your system port 8888 to the docker image port 8888 and so now, you can fire up jupyter or jupyterlab in your local browser! If you would like to forward all exposed ports in a random fashion, use -P instead. These images come with Anaconda\u2019s python distribution and as I mentioned earlier you can start with any image to add additional tools by using your dockerfile and building locally.", "For my use, I have added Julia, Python27 and Python36 environments using Anaconda to the all-spark-notebook image.", "This modified image contains the following kernels accessible from Jupyter :", "The repository for my image is on Github for you to use and modify as you see fit. To use this environment and mount a local directory for work, run it using :", "The above command does 3 important steps :1. Download and Run container cvbi/datascience-environment2. Forward all exposed container ports to random host environment ports3. mount the host directory \u201cpath_to_shared_local_directory\u201d to access from container at /home/jovyan/work/", "Once you are done running the above command, copy jupyter token and see the port mapping using :", "Open your browser to access the said ports e.g localhost:32780 and paste your key to access this Jupyter environment.", "Caution : Adding software to an image means increasing total image size (obviously), so building on top of another image will most certainly increase the total download size for the first run.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Interested in applied machine learning, statistics and data science"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsc